western expansion and the psychological challenges of new identities came together in ways that could help or hurt American health. From his vantage point at one of the nation's few medical schools, located in its intellectual capital, Rush developed a reputation as America's physician—while mixing social and scientific ideas for the "improvement" of the country as a whole. Putting Rush in this context, Benjamin Rush, Civic Health, and Human Illness in the Early American Republic goes beyond biography to explore his social and scientific networks and their role in the development of a distinctly American medical profession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducatorsvBiographyzUnited States. 0aEducatorszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPhysiciansvBiographyzUnited States. 0aPhysicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aBiography & Memoirs. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aAmerican Revolution.  aFounding Fathers.  aPhiladelphia.  aearly republic.  amedical history.  amedicine.  apublic health.  arepublicanism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805430261?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805430261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805430261/original  a978-3-11-142849-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles